            </div>-->
            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                <p>(The stone) of <persName xml:lang="cel">Bodvocus</persName>. Here he lies, the son of <persName xml:lang="cel">Catotogirnus</persName> and great-grandson of <persName xml:lang="cel">Eternalis Vedomavus</persName>.</p>
            </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The Welsh Corpus (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 407) notes that <q>the ancient British name BODVOC appears on coins of the Dobunni, and <persName xml:lang="cel">Bodvocus</persName> occurs beside <persName xml:lang="cel">Bodvacus</persName> in Gaul</q> . The name CATOTIGIRNI is most likely Brittonic <q>the precursor of OW <persName xml:lang="owl">Cattegirn</persName>, Pr.B. <persName xml:lang="cel">Catihernus</persName>...VEDOMAVI contains W. <foreign xml:lang="cy">gŵydd</foreign>, "wild". This stem does appear as well in ogam, VEDA-, VEDDO-, but the phonetic development of the second element...proves the name to be Brittonic rather than Irish</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 407). There is some debate surrounding the relationship between the inscription and the incised cross on the top of the stone. Some have suggested that the cross was carved at the same time as the inscription, but it is most likely a later addition (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 407). <q>There was a tradition associated with the stone that whoever read the inscription correctly would die soon afterwards/within a year of that date</q> (Macalister 1945, 384-385; Redknap and Lewis 2007, 408).</p>
            </div>
